SIMPLE: reprobate
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Reprobate
<hw>Rep"ro*bate</hw> <pr>(-b?t)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>reprobatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>reprobare</ets> to disapprove,
condemn. See <er>Reprieve</er>, <er>Reprove</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Not enduring proof or trial; not of standard purity
or fineness; disallowed; rejected.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Reprobate</qex> silver shall men call them, because the Lord
hath rejected them.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. vi. 30.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Abandoned to punishment; hence, morally abandoned
and lost; given up to vice; depraved.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And strength, and art, are easily outdone⟦br⟧
By spirits <qex>reprobate</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to one who is given up to
wickedness; <as>as, <ex>reprobate</ex> conduct</as>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Reprobate</xex> desire.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Abandoned; vitiated; depraved; corrupt; wicked;
profligate; base; vile. See <er>Abandoned</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Reprobate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Reprobate
<hw>Rep"ro*bate</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One morally abandoned and
lost.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I acknowledge myself for a <qex>reprobate</qex>, a villain, a
traitor to the king.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Raleigh.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Reprobate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Reprobate
<hw>Rep"ro*bate</hw> <pr>(-b?t)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Reprobated</conjf>
<pr>(-b?`t?d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Reprobating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To disapprove
with detestation or marks of extreme dislike; to condemn as unworthy; to
disallow; to reject.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such an answer as this is <qex>reprobated</qex> and disallowed of
in law; I do not believe it, unless the deed appears.</q>
<rj><qau>Ayliffe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Every scheme, every person, recommended by one of them, was
<qex>reprobated</qex> by the other.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To abandon to punishment without hope of
pardon.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To condemn; reprehend; censure; disown; abandon;
reject.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Reprobateness</ent>⟦br⟧
